# Git attributes for JobbPiloten
# Round-74 closeout followup — tighten scope so binary assets in /public/
# (PNGs, ICOs, SVGs, PDFs, WebP) are NOT subjected to LF line-ending
# normalization. The earlier catch-all `* text=auto eol=lf` would have
# corrupted binary bytes on first Windows clone.

# --- 1. Source text files: lock LF on checkout (clobbers CRLF → LF) ---
# Scope explicitly to text extensions. Adding a new source file in a
# new extension requires editing this file; if that becomes a chore
# we can swap to repository config (core.autocrlf=false + core.eol=lf).
*.js		text eol=lf
*.mjs		text eol=lf
*.jsx		text eol=lf
*.ts		text eol=lf
*.tsx		text eol=lf
*.css		text eol=lf
*.scss		text eol=lf
*.html		text eol=lf
*.md		text eol=lf
*.json		text eol=lf
*.yml		text eol=lf
*.yaml		text eol=lf
*.sh		text eol=lf
*.py		text eol=lf

# --- 2. env.template: pin UTF-8 + LF (defense in depth) ---
# This is the file most likely to trip Windows clients because of
# the em-dash byte. Explicit text + utf-8 + eol=lf prevents any
# round-trip mangling even if the catch-all is later expanded.
.env.template	text=utf-8	eol=lf

# --- 3. Binary assets: mark explicit so git never tries normalization ---
# Anything NOT in the source-text list above falls through to the
# repository default (text=auto). The list below forces git to
# treat these as binary even if auto-detection misclassifies them.
*.png	binary
*.ico	binary
*.jpg	binary
*.jpeg	binary
*.gif	binary
*.webp	binary
*.pdf	binary
*.zip	binary
*.gz	binary
*.tar	binary
*.woff	binary
*.woff2	binary
*.ttf	binary
*.eot	binary
*.otf	binary
*.mp3	binary
*.mp4	binary
*.webm	binary
